"266":{"department":"MATH","number":"266","title":"Computational Signal Processing and Wavelets","description":"Theoretical and computational aspects of signal processing. Topics: time-frequency transforms; wavelet bases and wavelet packets; linear and nonlinear multiresolution approximations; estimation and restoration of signals; signal compression. May be repeated for credit.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":117496,},
"269":{"department":"MATH","number":"269","title":"Topics in symplectic geometry","description":"May be repeated for credit.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":117505,"primary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:00:00 AM","end":"12:15:00 PM","location":"Herrin T185"}],"id":30297}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"270":{"department":"MATH","number":"270","title":"Geometry and Topology of Complex Manifolds","description":"Complex manifolds, Kahler manifolds, curvature, Hodge theory, Lefschetz theorem, Kahler-Einstein equation, Hermitian-Einstein equations, deformation of complex structures. May be repeated for credit.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":117506,},
"271":{"department":"MATH","number":"271","title":"The H-Principle","description":"The language of jets. Thom transversality theorem. Holonomic approximation theorem. Applications: immersion theory and its generaliazations. Differential relations and  Gromov's h-principle for open manifolds. Applications to symplectic geometry. Microflexibility. Mappings with simple singularities and their applications. Method of convex integration. Nash-Kuiper  C^1-isometric embedding theorem.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":117507,},
